               <msContents>
                  <summary>
                     <title type="uniform">Skånske kirkelov</title>
                     <origPlace key="DK">Denmark</origPlace>
                     <origDate notBefore="1650" notAfter="1699">later half of the 17th century</origDate>
                  </summary>
                  <msItem n="1" class="logfr" defective="false">
                     <locus from="1r" to="8v">1r-8v</locus>
                     <title type="uniform">Skånske kirkelov</title>
                     <textLang mainLang="da">Danish</textLang>
                     <rubric>Schaansche Kierche Loug</rubric>
                     <rubric>Kierchen wijes: Capt: 1.</rubric>
                     <incipit>Worder kierche wiitt, da shall hun</incipit>
                     <explicit>effter denne Loug for fölgis.</explicit>
                     <filiation>For filiation information see <bibl><ref target="DGL1-1">Johs. Brøndum-Nielsen,
                           Svend Aakjær: Danmarks gamle Landskabslove med Kirkelovene,
                           vol. I:1 (1933), </ref><biblScope type="pages"
                              >cxlv &amp; 879</biblScope></bibl>.</filiation> 
                     <note>There is an edition of the text using the main manuscript GkS 
                        3125 4to, with a variant apparatus, incl. <ref type="ms" target="AM04-0038-a">AM 38 a 4to</ref> (<bibl><ref
                           type="second-1" target="DGL1-2">Svend Aakjær, Erik Kroman:
                           Danmarks gamle Landskabslove med Kirkelovene, vol. I:2
                            (1933), </ref><biblScope type="pages"
                              >879.</biblScope></bibl></note>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               
               
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support>Paper with watermark. <watermark>On fol. 2+7, 4+5 (coat of arms
                           of Amsterdam); countermark 1+8 and 3+6 ("DC").</watermark>
                        </support>
                        <extent>8 leaves. <dimensions type="leaf" scope="all">
                           <height unit="mm" atLeast="200" atMost="204">200-204</height>
                           <width unit="mm" atLeast="157" atMost="159">157-159</width>
                        </dimensions>
                           <note>The final leaf has been trimmed slightly more than the
                              others (width 154 mm).</note>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation><p>Later foliation in dark grey ink on each recto-page. The numbers 4, 6 and 7 have
                        been redrawn in black ink.</p></foliation>
                        <collation><p>There is one quire: <list>
                           <item>I: fols. 1-8 (1+8, 2+7, 3+6, 4+5)</item>
                        </list>
                        </p>
                           <catchwords>There are no catchwords.</catchwords>
                        </collation>
                        <condition>
                           <p>The paper is rather light with slight discoloration around the edges and on fol. <locus>8v</locus>.</p>
                           <p>There is slight moisture damage on the edges of the
                              leaves, mostly in the lower outer corner.</p>
                           <p>A small tear in the outer margin of fol. <locus>1</locus> has been repaired by means of Japanese paper.</p>
                           <p>A small piece is torn from the lower margin of fol. <locus>4</locus>, which does not affect the text.</p>
                           <p>Generally in good condition.</p>
                        </condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" writtenLines="18 23">
                           <p>The manuscript is written in one column with 18 to 23 lines
                              per page and ca. 9 words per line.</p>
                           <p>The dimensions of the written area are on average 158 mm (height), 118 mm (width).
                              <dimensions type="written">
                                 <height unit="mm" atLeast="148" atMost="171">148-171</height>
                                 <width unit="mm" atLeast="110" atMost="123">110-123</width>
                              </dimensions></p>
                           <p>The wider margin is always on the left side of the written area, also on recto-pages.</p>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc hands="1">
                     <handNote scribe="unknown" scope="sole" script="kurrent"> 
                        <p>A single unknown scribe; main body written in kurrent script; chapter headings and rubric written in chancery.
                        </p></handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote type="initial">There are penwork initials up to two lines in height for the chapter headings and the rubric. Black is the only ink used. 
                     </decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  
                  <additions>
                     <p>On the front pastedown, the shelfmark and other catalogue related marks are added.</p>
                     <p>On fol. <locus>1r</locus>, <q>N 38</q> was added in large script above the title of the text.
                     At first, this shelfmark number was written in reddish-brown crayon, but later it was redrawn in black ink.</p>
                  </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding contemporary="false" notBefore="1771" notAfter="1780">
                        <p>Grey cardboard binding from ca. <date>1771-1780</date> with pastedowns from printed material.</p>
                        <p>Two of Kålund's labels on the spine: the upper one for the shelfmark is square and turquoise (580
                           mm in height), the lower one for the running number is circular and white.</p>
                        <p>On the front board, <q>No 38. A Skaanske Kircke Loug.</q> is written in black ink. Orignally, the letter of the shelfmark
                        was <q>B</q>, but was later crossed out at substituted with a superscript <q>A</q> in lighter brown ink. 
                       </p>
                        <p>This manuscript is stored in one box together with <ref target="AM04-0038-b">AM 38 b 4to</ref>.</p>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  
                  <accMat>
                  </accMat>
